# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: redox-reactions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] In chemistry, **disproportionation**, sometimes called **dismutation** (the French word), is a redox reaction in which one compound of intermediate oxidation state converts to two compounds, one of higher and one of lower oxidation state.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] The reverse of disproportionation, such as when a compound in an intermediate oxidation state is formed from precursors of lower and higher oxidation states, is called *comproportionation*, also known as *symproportionation*.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] This expanded definition is not limited to redox reactions, but also includes some molecular autoionization reactions, such as the self-ionization of water.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] In contrast, some authors use the term *redistribution* to refer to reactions of this type (in either direction) when only ligand exchange but no redox is involved and distinguish such processes from disproportionation and comproportionation.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] is an example of a redistribution reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] This was examined using tartrates by Johan Gadolin in 1788.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] In the Swedish version of his paper he called it *söndring*.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] The oxidation numbers remain constant in this acid-base reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] ion is +5, indicating that it has been oxidized.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] in the superoxide free radical anion, −1 in hydrogen peroxide and 0 in dioxygen.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] In free-radical chain-growth polymerization, chain termination can occur by a disproportionation step in which a hydrogen atom is transferred from one growing chain molecule to another one, which produces two dead (non-growing) chains.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] in which, Chain— represents the already formed polymer chain, and • indicates a reactive free radical.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] The dismutation of pyruvic acid into other small organic molecules (ethanol + CO2, or lactate and acetate, depending on the environmental conditions) is also a key step in fermentation reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Fermentation reactions can also be considered as disproportionation or dismutation biochemical reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Indeed, the donor and acceptor of electrons in the redox reactions supplying the chemical energy in these complex biochemical systems are the same organic molecules simultaneously acting as reductant or oxidant.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Another example of biochemical dismutation reaction is the disproportionation of acetaldehyde into ethanol and acetic acid.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] In cellular respiration, electrons are transferred from substrate (electron donor) to an electron acceptor; in fermentation, part of the substrate molecule itself accepts the electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Fermentation is therefore a type of disproportionation, and does not involve an overall change in oxidation state of the substrate.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Most of the fermentative substrates are organic molecules.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Another example is microbial sulfur disproportionation (MSD), a type of energy metabolism involving the disproportionation of inorganic sulfur compounds, that exists often alongside reduction of sulfate in certain bacteria.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Sulfur isotopes of sediments are often measured for studying environments in the Earth's past (paleoenvironment).
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Disproportionation of sulfur intermediates, being one of the processes affecting sulfur isotopes of sediments, has drawn attention from geoscientists for studying the redox conditions in the oceans in the past.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Sulfate-reducing bacteria fractionate sulfur isotopes as they take in sulfate and produce sulfide.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Prior to 2010s, it was thought that sulfate reduction could fractionate sulfur isotopes up to 46 ‰ and fractionation larger than 46 ‰ recorded in sediments must be due to disproportionation of sulfur intermediates in the sediment.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] As substrates for disproportionation are limited by the product of sulfate reduction, the isotopic effect of disproportionation should be less than 16 ‰ in most sedimentary settings.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Disproportionation can be carried out by obligate disproportionators or, more often, by microorganisms that can carry out sulfate reduction or sulfur oxidation as well.
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] Common substrates for disproportionation include elemental sulfur (S8), thiosulfate (S2O2−3) and sulfite (SO2−3).
[src:redox-reactions/disproportionation] The Claus reaction is one of the chemical reactions involved in the Claus process used for the desulfurization of gases in the oil refinery plants and leading to the formation of solid elemental sulfur (S8), which is easier to store, transport, reuse when possible, and dispose of.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] In chemistry, a **half reaction** (or **half-cell reaction**) is either the oxidation or reduction reaction component of a redox reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] A half reaction is obtained by considering the change in oxidation states of individual substances involved in the redox reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Often, the concept of half reactions is used to describe what occurs in an electrochemical cell, such as a Galvanic cell battery at one of the two electrodes.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] In the case of metal plating and metal stripping the same half reaction can be written to describe both the metal undergoing oxidation (known as the anode) and the metal undergoing reduction (known as the cathode).
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Half reactions are often used as a method of balancing redox reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] For oxidation-reduction reactions in acidic conditions, after balancing the atoms and oxidation numbers, H+ ions must be added to balance the hydrogen ions in the half reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] For oxidation-reduction reactions in basic conditions, after balancing the atoms and oxidation numbers, it must be treated as an acidic solution, and then OH− ions must be added to balance the H+ ions in the half reactions (which would give H2O).
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] The Galvanic cell shown in the adjacent image is constructed with a piece of zinc (Zn) submerged in a solution of zinc sulfate (ZnSO4) and a piece of copper (Cu) submerged in a solution of copper(II) sulfate (CuSO4).
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] At the Zn anode, oxidation takes place, meaning the metal loses electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] At the Cu cathode, reduction takes place, meaning electrons are gained or accepted.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Consider the example burning of magnesium ribbon (Mg).
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Magnesium oxide is an ionic compound containing Mg2+ and O2− ions whereas Mg(s) and O2(g) are elements with no charges.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] The Mg(s) with zero charge gains a +2 charge going from the reactant side to product side, and the O2(g) with zero charge gains a −2 charge.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] This is because when Mg(s) becomes Mg2+, it loses 2 electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] On the other hand, O2 was reduced: its oxidation state goes from 0 to −2.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] When chemical reaction, especially, redox reaction takes place, the naked eye cannot see the electrons as they appear and disappear during the course of the reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Instead, observers see the reactants and end products.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Due to this, electrons appearing on both sides of the equation are canceled.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Two ions, positive (Mg2+) and negative (O2−), exist on product side, and they combine immediately to form the magnesium oxide (MgO) compound due to their opposite charges (electrostatic attraction).
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] In any given oxidation-reduction reaction, there are two half reactions: the oxidation half reaction and the reduction half reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] The sum of these two half reactions is the oxidation–reduction reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] The two elements involved, iron and chlorine, each change oxidation state; iron from +2 to +3, chlorine from 0 to −1.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] There are then effectively two *half* reactions occurring.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Given two half reactions it is possible, with knowledge of appropriate electrode potentials, to arrive at the complete (original) reaction the same way.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] The decomposition of a reaction into half reactions is key to understanding a variety of chemical processes.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] For example, in the above reaction, it can be shown that this is a redox reaction in which Fe is oxidised, and Cl is reduced (so there is a transfer of electrons from Fe to Cl).
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Decomposition is also a way to simplify the balancing of a chemical equation.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] A chemist can atom balance and charge balance one piece of an equation at a time.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] It is also possible–sometimes necessary–to consider a half reaction in either basic or acidic conditions, as there may be an acidic or basic electrolyte involved in the redox reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Due to this electrolyte, it may be more difficult to satisfy the balance of both the atoms and charges; this is done by adding H2O, OH−, e−, and/or H+ to either side of the reaction until both atoms and charges are balanced.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] OH−, H2O, and e− can be used to balance the charges and atoms in basic conditions, as long as it is assumed that the reaction is in water.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] H+, H2O, and e− can be used to balance the charges and atoms in acidic conditions, as long as it is assumed that the reaction is in water.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Both sides are charge balanced, meaning the overall charge is neutral, and atom balanced, meaning there are equal numbers of each element on both sides.
[src:redox-reactions/half-reaction] Often there will be both H+ and OH− present in acidic and basic conditions, but the resulting reaction of the two ions will yield water.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In chemistry, the **oxidation state**, or **oxidation number**, is the hypothetical charge of an atom if all of its bonds to other atoms are fully ionic.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] It describes the degree of oxidation (loss of electrons) of an atom in a chemical compound.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Conceptually, the oxidation state may be positive, negative or zero.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Beside nearly-pure ionic bonding, many covalent bonds exhibit a strong ionicity, making oxidation state a useful predictor of charge.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The oxidation state of an atom does not represent the "real" charge on that atom, or any other actual atomic property.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This is particularly true of high oxidation states, where the ionization energy required to produce a multiply positive ion is far greater than the energies available in chemical reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Additionally, the oxidation states of atoms in a given compound may vary depending on the choice of electronegativity scale used in their calculation.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Thus, the oxidation state of an atom in a compound is purely a formalism.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] It is nevertheless important in understanding the nomenclature conventions of inorganic compounds.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Also, several observations regarding chemical reactions may be explained at a basic level in terms of oxidation states.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Oxidation states are typically represented by integers which may be positive, zero, or negative.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In some cases, the average oxidation state of an element is a fraction, such as ⁠8/3⁠ for iron in magnetite Fe3O4 (see below).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The highest known oxidation state is reported to be +9, displayed by iridium in the tetroxoiridium(IX) cation (IrO+4).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] It is predicted that even a +10 oxidation state may be achieved by platinum in tetroxoplatinum(X), PtO2+4.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The lowest oxidation state is −5, as for boron in Al3BC and gallium in pentamagnesium digallide (Mg5Ga2).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In Stock nomenclature, which is commonly used for inorganic compounds, the oxidation state is represented by a Roman numeral placed after the element name inside parentheses, e.g.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Iron(III) oxide, or as a superscript after the element symbol, e.g.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The term *oxidation* was first used by Antoine Lavoisier to signify the reaction of a substance with oxygen.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Much later, it was realized that the substance, upon being oxidized, loses electrons, and the meaning was extended to include other reactions in which electrons are lost, regardless of whether oxygen was involved.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The increase in the oxidation state of an atom, through a chemical reaction, is known as oxidation; a decrease in oxidation state is known as a reduction.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Such reactions involve the formal transfer of electrons: a net gain in electrons being a reduction, and a net loss of electrons being oxidation.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For pure elements, the oxidation state is zero.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Oxidation numbers are assigned to elements in a molecule such that the overall sum is zero in a neutral molecule.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The number indicates the degree of oxidation of each element caused by molecular bonding.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In ionic compounds, the oxidation numbers are the same as the element's ionic charge.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Thus for KCl, potassium is assigned +1 and chlorine is assigned −1.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The complete set of rules for assigning oxidation numbers are discussed in the following sections.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Oxidation numbers are fundamental to the chemical nomenclature of ionic compounds.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For example, Cu compounds with Cu oxidation state +2 are called *cupric* and those with state +1 are *cuprous*.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The oxidation numbers of elements allow predictions of chemical formula and reactions, especially oxidation-reduction reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The oxidation numbers of the most stable chemical compounds follow trends in the periodic table.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) has published a "Comprehensive definition of oxidation state (IUPAC Recommendations 2016)".
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] It is a distillation of an IUPAC technical report: "Toward a comprehensive definition of oxidation state".
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] According to the IUPAC *Gold Book*: "The oxidation state of an atom is the charge of this atom after ionic approximation of its heteronuclear bonds." The term *oxidation number* is nearly synonymous.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The ionic approximation means extrapolating bonds to ionic.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Assignment of electrons according to the atom's contribution to the bonding Molecular orbital (MO) or the electron's allegiance in a LCAO–MO model.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In a bond between two different elements, the bond's electrons are assigned to its main atomic contributor typically of higher electronegativity; in a bond between two atoms of the same element, the electrons are divided equally.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Most electronegativity scales depend on the atom's bonding state, which makes the assignment of the oxidation state a somewhat circular argument.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For example, some scales may turn out unusual oxidation states, such as −6 for platinum in PtH2−4, for Pauling and Mulliken scales.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The dipole moments would sometimes also turn out abnormal oxidation numbers, such as in CO and NO, which are oriented with their positive end towards oxygen.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Therefore, this leaves the atom's contribution to the bonding MO, the atomic-orbital energy, and from quantum-chemical calculations of charges, as the only viable criteria with cogent values for ionic approximation.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] While introductory levels of chemistry teaching use postulated oxidation states, the IUPAC recommendation and the *Gold Book* entry list two entirely general algorithms for the calculation of the oxidation states of elements in chemical compounds.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Introductory chemistry uses postulates: the oxidation state for an element in a chemical formula is calculated from the overall charge and postulated oxidation states for all the other atoms.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This approach yields correct oxidation states in oxides and hydroxides of any single element, and in acids such as sulfuric acid (H2SO4) or dichromic acid (H2Cr2O7).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Its coverage can be extended either by a list of exceptions or by assigning priority to the postulates.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The latter works for hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) where the priority of rule 1 leaves both oxygens with oxidation state −1.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Additional postulates and their ranking may expand the range of compounds to fit a textbook's scope.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In a compound or ion, the sum of the oxidation states equals the total charge of the compound or ion.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Fluorine in compounds has OS = −1; this extends to chlorine and bromine only when not bonded to a lighter halogen, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Group 1 and group 2 metals in compounds have OS = +1 and +2, respectively.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Hydrogen has OS = +1 but adopts −1 when bonded as a hydride to metals or metalloids.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Oxygen in compounds has OS = −2 but only when not bonded to oxygen (e.g. in peroxides) or fluorine.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This set of postulates covers oxidation states of fluorides, chlorides, bromides, oxides, hydroxides, and hydrides of any single element.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] It covers all oxoacids of any central atom (and all their fluoro-, chloro-, and bromo-relatives), as well as salts of such acids with group 1 and 2 metals.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] It also covers iodides, sulfides, and similar simple salts of these metals.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This algorithm is performed on a Lewis structure (a diagram that shows all valence electrons).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] where each "—" represents an electron pair (either shared between two atoms or solely on one atom), and "OS" is the oxidation state as a numerical variable.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This example shows the importance of describing the bonding.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Its summary formula, HNO3, corresponds to two structural isomers; the peroxynitrous acid in the above figure and the more stable nitric acid.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] With the formula HNO3, the simple approach without bonding considerations yields −2 for all three oxygens and +5 for nitrogen, which is correct for nitric acid.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For the peroxynitrous acid, however, both oxygens in the O–O bond have OS = −1, and the nitrogen has OS = +3, which requires a structure to understand.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In some cases, this leads to alternative formulae that differ in bond orders (the full set of which is called the resonance formulas).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Consider the sulfate anion (SO2−4) with 32 valence electrons; 24 from oxygens, 6 from sulfur, 2 of the anion charge obtained from the implied cation.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The bond orders to the terminal oxygens do not affect the oxidation state so long as the oxygens have octets.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The bond-order formula at the bottom is closest to the reality of four equivalent oxygens each having a total bond order of 2.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] That total includes the bond of order ⁠1/2⁠ to the implied cation and follows the 8 − *N* rule requiring that the main-group atom's bond-order total equals 8 − *N* valence electrons of the neutral atom, enforced with a priority that proportionately increases with electronegativity.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This algorithm works equally for molecular cations composed of several atoms.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Drawing Lewis structures with electron pairs as dashes emphasizes the essential equivalence of bond pairs and lone pairs when counting electrons and moving bonds onto atoms.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The algorithm contains a caveat, which concerns rare cases of transition-metal complexes with a type of ligand that is reversibly bonded as a Lewis acid (as an acceptor of the electron pair from the transition metal); termed a "Z-type" ligand in Green's covalent bond classification method.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The caveat originates from the simplifying use of electronegativity instead of the MO-based electron allegiance to decide the ionic sign.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] One early example is the O2S−RhCl(CO)(PPh3)2 complex with sulfur dioxide (SO2) as the reversibly-bonded acceptor ligand (released upon heating).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] illustrates that, in this algorithm, homonuclear bonds are simply ignored (the bond orders are in blue).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] To obtain the oxidation states, the formal charges are summed with the bond-order value taken positively at the carbon and negatively at the oxygen.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Applied to molecular ions, this algorithm considers the actual location of the formal (ionic) charge, as drawn in the Lewis structure.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The sum of oxidation states in the ion equals its charge (as it equals zero for a neutral molecule).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Also in anions, the formal (ionic) charges have to be considered when nonzero.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] A bond graph in solid-state chemistry is a chemical formula of an extended structure, in which direct bonding connectivities are shown.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] We see that the oxygen atom bonds to the six nearest rubidium cations, each of which has 4 bonds to the auride anion.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The bond graph summarizes these connectivities.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The bond orders (also called bond valences) sum up to oxidation states according to the attached sign of the bond's ionic approximation (there are no formal charges in bond graphs).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Determination of oxidation states from a bond graph can be illustrated on ilmenite, FeTiO3.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] We may ask whether the mineral contains Fe2+ and Ti4+, or Fe3+ and Ti3+.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Its crystal structure has each metal atom bonded to six oxygens and each of the equivalent oxygens to two irons and two titaniums, as in the bond graph below.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Experimental data show that three metal-oxygen bonds in the octahedron are short and three are long (the metals are off-center).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Oxidation states can be useful for balancing chemical equations for oxidation-reduction (or redox) reactions, because the changes in the oxidized atoms have to be balanced by the changes in the reduced atoms.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For example, in the reaction of acetaldehyde with Tollens' reagent to form acetic acid (shown below), the carbonyl carbon atom changes its oxidation state from +1 to +3 (loses two electrons).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This oxidation is balanced by reducing two Ag+ cations to Ag0 (gaining two electrons in total).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] An inorganic example is the Bettendorf reaction using tin dichloride (SnCl2) to prove the presence of arsenite ions in a concentrated HCl extract.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Here three tin atoms are oxidized from oxidation state +2 to +4, yielding six electrons that reduce two arsenic atoms from oxidation state +3 to 0.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] One tin is oxidized from oxidation state +2 to +4, a two-electron step, hence 2 is written in front of the two arsenic partners.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] One arsenic is reduced from +3 to 0, a three-electron step, hence 3 goes in front of the two tin partners.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] An alternative three-line procedure is to write separately the half-reactions for oxidation and reduction, each balanced with electrons, and then to sum them up such that the electrons cross out.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In general, these redox balances (the one-line balance or each half-reaction) need to be checked for the ionic and electron charge sums on both sides of the equation being indeed equal.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] If they are not equal, suitable ions are added to balance the charges and the non-redox elemental balance.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Both alternative oxidation numbers for phosphorus make chemical sense, depending on which chemical property or reaction is emphasized.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] By contrast, a calculated alternative, such as the average (+4) does not.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Lewis formulae are rule-based approximations of chemical reality, as are Allen electronegativities.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Still, oxidation states may seem ambiguous when their determination is not straightforward.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] If only an experiment can determine the oxidation state, the rule-based determination is ambiguous (insufficient).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] There are also truly dichotomous values that are decided arbitrarily.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Seemingly ambiguous oxidation states are derived from a set of resonance formulas of equal weights for a molecule having heteronuclear bonds where the atom connectivity does not correspond to the number of two-electron bonds dictated by the 8 − *N* rule.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] An example is S2N2 where four resonance formulas featuring one S=N double bond have oxidation states +2 and +4 for the two sulfur atoms, which average to +3 because the two sulfur atoms are equivalent in this square-shaped molecule.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] is needed to reveal that this bond order is very close to 1, as in the formula on the left.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] is +1, which also obtains for both nitrogens by a molecular orbital approach.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The formal charges on the right comply with electronegativities, which implies an added ionic bonding contribution.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Conversely, formal charges against electronegativities in a Lewis structure decrease the bond order of the corresponding bond.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Fractional oxidation states are often used to represent the average oxidation state of several atoms of the same element in a structure.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For example, the formula of magnetite is Fe3O4, implying an average oxidation state for iron of +⁠8/3⁠.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] However, this average value may not be representative if the atoms are not equivalent.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In a Fe3O4 crystal below 120 K (−153 °C), two-thirds of the cations are Fe3+ and one-third are Fe2+, and the formula may be more clearly represented as FeO·Fe2O3.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Likewise, propane, C3H8, has been described as having a carbon oxidation state of −⁠8/3⁠.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Again, this is an average value since the structure of the molecule is H3C−CH2−CH3, with the first and third carbon atoms each having an oxidation state of −3 and the central one −2.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] An example with true fractional oxidation states for equivalent atoms is potassium superoxide, KO2.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The diatomic superoxide ion O−2 has an overall charge of −1, so each of its two equivalent oxygen atoms is assigned an oxidation state of −⁠1/2⁠.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This ion can be described as a resonance hybrid of two Lewis structures, where each oxygen has an oxidation state of 0 in one structure and −1 in the other.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For the cyclopentadienyl anion C5H−5, the oxidation state of C is −1 + −⁠1/5⁠ = −⁠6/5⁠.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The −1 occurs because each carbon is bonded to one hydrogen atom (a less electronegative element), and the −⁠1/5⁠ because the total ionic charge of −1 is divided among five equivalent carbons.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Again this can be described as a resonance hybrid of five equivalent structures, each having four carbons with oxidation state −1 and one with −2.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Finally, fractional oxidation numbers **are not used** in the chemical nomenclature.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For example the red lead Pb3O4 is represented as lead(II,IV) oxide, showing the oxidation states of the two nonequivalent lead atoms.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Most elements have more than one possible oxidation state.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Many compounds with luster and electrical conductivity maintain a simple stoichiometric formula, such as the golden TiO, blue-black RuO2 or coppery ReO3, all of obvious oxidation state.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Ultimately, assigning the free metallic electrons to one of the bonded atoms is not comprehensive and can yield unusual oxidation states.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Examples are the LiPb and Cu3Au ordered alloys, the composition and structure of which are largely determined by atomic size and packing factors.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Should oxidation state be needed for redox balancing, it is best set to 0 for all atoms of such an alloy.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This is a list of known oxidation states of the chemical elements, excluding nonintegral values.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The table is based on that of Greenwood and Earnshaw, with additions noted.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Every element exists in oxidation state 0 when it is the pure non-ionized element in any phase, whether monatomic or polyatomic allotrope.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The column for oxidation state 0 only shows elements known to exist in oxidation state 0 in compounds.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] A figure with a similar format was used by Irving Langmuir in 1919 in one of the early papers about the octet rule.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The periodicity of the oxidation states was one of the pieces of evidence that led Langmuir to adopt the rule.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The oxidation state in compound naming for transition metals and lanthanides and actinides is placed either as a right superscript to the element symbol in a chemical formula, such as FeIII or in parentheses after the name of the element in chemical names, such as iron(III).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For example, Fe2(SO4)3 is named iron(III) sulfate and its formula can be shown as FeIII2(SO4)3.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This is because a sulfate ion has a charge of −2, so each iron atom takes a charge of +3.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Oxidation itself was first studied by Antoine Lavoisier, who defined it as the result of reactions with oxygen (hence the name).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The term has since been generalized to imply a *formal* loss of electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Oxidation states, called *oxidation grades* by Friedrich Wöhler in 1835, were one of the intellectual stepping stones that Dmitri Mendeleev used to derive the periodic table.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Jensen gives an overview of the history up to 1938.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] When it was realized that some metals form two different binary compounds with the same nonmetal, the two compounds were often distinguished by using the ending *-ic* for the higher metal oxidation state and the ending *-ous* for the lower.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] For example, FeCl3 is ferric chloride and FeCl2 is ferrous chloride.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This system is not very satisfactory (although sometimes still used) because different metals have different oxidation states which have to be learned: ferric and ferrous are +3 and +2 respectively, but cupric and cuprous are +2 and +1, and stannic and stannous are +4 and +2.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Also, there was no allowance for metals with more than two oxidation states, such as vanadium with oxidation states +2, +3, +4, and +5.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This system has been largely replaced by one suggested by Alfred Stock in 1919 and adopted by IUPAC in 1940.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Thus, FeCl2 was written as iron(II) chloride rather than ferrous chloride.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The Roman numeral II at the central atom came to be called the "Stock number" (now an obsolete term), and its value was obtained as a charge at the central atom after removing its ligands along with the electron pairs they shared with it.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The term "oxidation state" in English chemical literature was popularized by Wendell Mitchell Latimer in his 1938 book about electrochemical potentials.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] He used it for the value (synonymous with the German term *Wertigkeit*) previously termed "valence", "polar valence" or "polar number" in English, or "oxidation stage" or indeed the "state of oxidation".
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] Since 1938, the term "oxidation state" has been connected with electrochemical potentials and electrons exchanged in redox couples participating in redox reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] By 1948, IUPAC used the 1940 nomenclature rules with the term "oxidation state", instead of the original *valency*.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In 1948 Linus Pauling proposed that oxidation number could be determined by extrapolating bonds to being completely ionic in the direction of electronegativity.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] A full acceptance of this suggestion was complicated by the fact that the Pauling electronegativities as such depend on the oxidation state and that they may lead to unusual values of oxidation states for some transition metals.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] In 1990 IUPAC resorted to a postulatory (rule-based) method to determine the oxidation state.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This was complemented by the synonymous term oxidation number as a descendant of the Stock number introduced in 1940 into the nomenclature.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] However, the terminology using "ligands" gave the impression that oxidation number might be something specific to coordination complexes.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] This situation and the lack of a real single definition generated numerous debates about the meaning of oxidation state, suggestions about methods to obtain it and definitions of it.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] To resolve the issue, an IUPAC project (2008-040-1-200) was started in 2008 on the "Comprehensive Definition of Oxidation State", and was concluded by two reports and by the revised entries "Oxidation State" and "Oxidation Number" in the IUPAC Gold Book.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidation-state] The outcomes were a single definition of oxidation state and two algorithms to calculate it in molecular and extended-solid compounds, guided by Allen electronegativities that are independent of oxidation state.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] An **oxidizing agent** (also known as an **oxidant**, **oxidizer**, **electron recipient**, or **electron acceptor**) is a substance in a redox chemical reaction that gains or "accepts"/"receives" an electron from a *reducing agent* (called the *reductant*, *reducer*, or *electron donor*).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] In other words, an oxidizer is any substance that oxidizes another substance.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] The oxidation state, which describes the degree of loss of electrons, of the oxidizer decreases while that of the reductant increases; this is expressed by saying that oxidizers "undergo reduction" and "are reduced" while reducers "undergo oxidation" and "are oxidized".
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] Common oxidizing agents are oxygen, hydrogen peroxide, and the halogens.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] In one sense, an oxidizing agent is a chemical species that undergoes a chemical reaction in which it gains one or more electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] In that sense, it is one component in an oxidation–reduction (redox) reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] In the second sense, an oxidizing agent is a chemical species that transfers electronegative atoms, usually oxygen, to a substrate.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] Combustion, many explosives, and organic redox reactions involve atom-transfer reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] Electron acceptors participate in electron-transfer reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] In this context, the oxidizing agent is called an *electron acceptor* and the reducing agent is called an *electron donor*.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] A classic oxidizing agent is the ferrocenium ion Fe(C 5H 5)+ 2, which accepts an electron to form Fe(C5H5)2.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] One of the strongest acceptors commercially available is "magic blue", the radical cation derived from N(C6H4-4-Br)3.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] For extensive tabulations of ranking the electron accepting properties of various reagents (redox potentials), see Standard electrode potential (data page).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] In more common usage, an oxidizing agent transfers oxygen atoms to a substrate.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] In this context, the oxidizing agent can be called an oxygenation reagent or oxygen-atom transfer (OAT) agent.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] Examples include MnO− 4 (permanganate), CrO2− 4 (chromate), OsO4 (osmium tetroxide), and especially ClO− 4 (perchlorate).
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] Notice that these species are all oxides.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] In some cases, these oxides can also serve as electron acceptors, as illustrated by the conversion of MnO− 4 to MnO2− 4, ie permanganate to manganate.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] The dangerous goods definition of an oxidizing agent is a substance that can cause or contribute to the combustion of other material.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] By this definition some materials that are classified as oxidizing agents by analytical chemists are not classified as oxidizing agents in a dangerous materials sense.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] An example is potassium dichromate, which does not pass the dangerous goods test of an oxidizing agent.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] Department of Transportation defines oxidizing agents specifically.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] There are two definitions for oxidizing agents governed under DOT regulations.
[src:redox-reactions/oxidizing-agent] These two are Class 5; Division 5.1(a)1 and Class 5; Division 5.1(a)2.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In electron transfer, usually a single electron flows from the atom, ion, or molecule being oxidized to the one being reduced, a case often described in terms of redox couples and electrode potentials.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In atom transfer, an atom passes from one substrate to another; for example, in the rusting of iron the oxidation state of the iron atoms increases as the metal converts to an oxide, while oxygen is reduced as it accepts the released electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Although oxidation is commonly associated with forming oxides, other chemical species can serve the same function; in hydrogenation, bonds such as C=C are reduced by the transfer of hydrogen atoms.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Redox reactions occur throughout nature and industry.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Cellular respiration and photosynthesis, combustion, and the corrosion of metals all proceed through redox chemistry, as do the reactions that power batteries and other electrochemical cells.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Industry uses redox reactions to extract metals from their ores by smelting, to electroplate objects, and to manufacture chemicals such as nitric acid; in soils, sediments, and water, redox gradients drive the biogeochemical cycling of elements.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] "Redox" is a portmanteau of "reduction" and "oxidation".
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The term was first used in a 1928 article by Leonor Michaelis and Louis B.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Oxidation is a process in which a substance loses electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Reduction is a process in which a substance gains electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The processes of oxidation and reduction occur simultaneously and cannot occur independently.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In redox processes, the reductant transfers electrons to the oxidant.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Thus, in the reaction, the reductant or reducer or reducing agent loses electrons and is oxidized, while the oxidant or oxidizer or oxidizing agent gains electrons and is reduced.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The pair of an oxidizing and reducing agent that is involved in a particular reaction is called a redox pair.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] A redox couple is a reducing species and its corresponding oxidizing form, e.g., Fe2+ / Fe3+ .The oxidation alone and the reduction alone are each called a *half-reaction* because two half-reactions always occur together to form a whole reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In electrochemical reactions the oxidation and reduction processes do occur simultaneously but are separated in space.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Oxidation originally implied a reaction with oxygen to form an oxide.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Later, the term was expanded to encompass substances that accomplished chemical reactions similar to those of oxygen.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Ultimately, the meaning was generalized to include all processes involving the loss of electrons or the increase in the oxidation state of a chemical species.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Substances that have the ability to oxidize other substances (cause them to lose electrons) are said to be oxidative or oxidizing, and are known as oxidizing agents, oxidants, or oxidizers.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The oxidant removes electrons from another substance, and is thus itself reduced.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Because it "accepts" electrons, the oxidizing agent is also called an electron acceptor.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Oxidants are usually chemical substances with elements in high oxidation states (e.g., N 2O 4, MnO− 4, CrO 3, Cr 2O2− 7, OsO 4), or else highly electronegative elements (e.g.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] O2, F2, Cl2, Br2, I2) that can gain extra electrons by oxidizing another substance.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Oxidizers are oxidants, but the term is mainly reserved for sources of oxygen, particularly in the context of explosions.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Substances that have the ability to reduce other substances (cause them to gain electrons) are said to be reductive or reducing and are known as reducing agents, reductants, or reducers.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The reductant transfers electrons to another substance and is thus itself oxidized.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Because it donates electrons, the reducing agent is also called an electron donor.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Electron donors can also form charge transfer complexes with electron acceptors.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The word reduction originally referred to the loss in weight upon heating a metallic ore such as a metal oxide to extract the metal.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In other words, ore was "reduced" to metal.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Antoine Lavoisier demonstrated that this loss of weight was due to the loss of oxygen as a gas.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Later, scientists realized that the metal atom gains electrons in this process.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The meaning of reduction then became generalized to include all processes involving a gain of electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Reducing equivalent refers to chemical species which transfer the equivalent of one electron in redox reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] A reducing equivalent can be an electron or a hydrogen atom as a hydride ion.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Reductants in chemistry are very diverse.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Electropositive elemental metals, such as lithium, sodium, magnesium, iron, zinc, and aluminium, are good reducing agents.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] These metals donate electrons relatively readily.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Hydride transfer reagents, such as NaBH4 and LiAlH4, reduce by atom transfer: they transfer the equivalent of hydride or H−.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] These reagents are widely used in the reduction of carbonyl compounds to alcohols.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] A related method of reduction involves the use of hydrogen gas (H2) as sources of H atoms.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The electrochemist John Bockris proposed the words electronation and de-electronation to describe reduction and oxidation processes, respectively, when they occur at electrodes.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] These words are analogous to protonation and deprotonation.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] IUPAC has recognized the terms electronation and de-electronation.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Redox reactions can occur slowly, as in the formation of rust, or rapidly, as in the case of burning fuel.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Electron transfer reactions are generally fast, occurring within the time of mixing.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The mechanisms of atom-transfer reactions are highly variable because many kinds of atoms can be transferred, and such reactions can involve several steps.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Electron-transfer reactions, by contrast, proceed by two distinct pathways.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In inner-sphere transfer, the two reactants share a bridging ligand through which the electron passes; in outer-sphere transfer, the electron moves between reactants whose coordination shells remain intact.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Henry Taube received the 1983 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for distinguishing these pathways through experiments on metal complexes.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The rate of an outer-sphere electron transfer is described by Marcus theory, developed by Rudolph A.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The theory expresses the activation energy in terms of two quantities: the standard free-energy change of the reaction and the reorganization energy, the energy needed to distort the reactants and the surrounding solvent into the configuration of the products before the electron moves.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] It predicts an "inverted region", in which the rate falls once the driving force exceeds the reorganization energy.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Marcus received the 1992 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the theory.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Analysis of bond energies and ionization energies in water allows calculation of the thermodynamic aspects of redox reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The electrode potential of each half-reaction is also known as its reduction potential (*E*o red), or potential when the half-reaction takes place at a cathode.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The reduction potential is a measure of the tendency of the oxidizing agent to be reduced.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Its value is zero for H+ + e− → 1⁄2H2 by definition, positive for oxidizing agents stronger than H+ (e.g., +2.866 V for F2) and negative for oxidizing agents that are weaker than H+ (e.g., −0.763V for Zn2+).
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The oxidation potential is a measure of the tendency of the reducing agent to be oxidized but does not represent the physical potential at an electrode.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] This spontaneous reaction releases a large amount of energy (542 kJ per 2 g of hydrogen) because two H-F bonds are much stronger than one H-H bond and one F-F bond.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] This reaction can be analyzed as two half-reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In this type of reaction, a metal atom in a compound or solution is replaced by an atom of another metal.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In the above reaction, zinc metal displaces the copper(II) ion from the copper sulfate solution, thus liberating free copper metal.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The reaction is spontaneous and releases 213 kJ per 65 g of zinc.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] A disproportionation reaction is one in which a single substance is both oxidized and reduced.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] For example, thiosulfate ion with sulfur in oxidation state +2 can react in the presence of acid to form elemental sulfur (oxidation state 0) and sulfur dioxide (oxidation state +4).
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Thus one sulfur atom is reduced from +2 to 0, while the other is oxidized from +2 to +4.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Cathodic protection is a technique used to control the corrosion of a metal surface by making it the cathode of an electrochemical cell.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] A simple method of protection connects protected metal to a more easily corroded "sacrificial anode" to act as the anode.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The sacrificial metal, instead of the protected metal, then corrodes.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Oxidation is used in many industries, such as in the production of cleaning products and oxidizing ammonia to produce nitric acid, whose principal industrial route is the catalytic oxidation of ammonia in the Ostwald process.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Redox reactions are the foundation of electrochemical cells, which can generate electrical energy or support electrosynthesis.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Metal ores often contain metals in oxidized states, such as oxides or sulfides, from which the pure metals are extracted by smelting at high temperatures in the presence of a reducing agent.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The process of electroplating uses redox reactions to coat objects with a thin layer of a material, as in chrome-plated automotive parts, silver plating cutlery, galvanization and gold-plated jewelry.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Many essential biological processes involve redox reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Before some of these processes can begin, iron must be assimilated from the environment.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Aerobic cellular respiration, for instance, is the oxidation of substrates [in this case: glucose (C6H12O6)] and the reduction of oxygen to water.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The process of cellular respiration also depends heavily on the reduction of NAD+ to NADH and the reverse reaction (the oxidation of NADH to NAD+).
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Biological energy is frequently stored and released using redox reactions.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Photosynthesis involves the reduction of carbon dioxide into sugars and the oxidation of water into molecular oxygen.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The reverse reaction, respiration, oxidizes sugars to produce carbon dioxide and water.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] As intermediate steps, the reduced carbon compounds are used to reduce nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) to NADH, which then contributes to the creation of a proton gradient, which drives the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and is maintained by the reduction of oxygen.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In animal cells, mitochondria perform similar functions.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The term *redox state* is often used to describe the balance of GSH/GSSG, NAD+/NADH and NADP+/NADPH in a biological system such as a cell or organ.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The redox state is reflected in the balance of several sets of metabolites (e.g., lactate and pyruvate, beta-hydroxybutyrate and acetoacetate), whose interconversion is dependent on these ratios.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Redox mechanisms also control some cellular processes.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Redox proteins and their genes must be co-located for redox regulation according to the CoRR hypothesis for the function of DNA in mitochondria and chloroplasts.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Many aromatic compounds are enzymatically reduced to form free radicals that contain one more electron than their parent compounds.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] In general, the electron donor is a flavoenzyme or one of its coenzymes.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Once formed, these anion free radicals reduce molecular oxygen to superoxide and regenerate the unchanged parent compound.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The net reaction is the oxidation of the flavoenzyme's coenzymes and the reduction of molecular oxygen to form superoxide.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] This catalytic behavior has been described as a futile cycle or redox cycling.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Minerals are generally oxidized derivatives of metals.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Iron is mined as ores such as magnetite (Fe3O4) and hematite (Fe2O3).
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Titanium is mined as its dioxide, usually in the form of rutile (TiO2).
[src:redox-reactions/redox] These oxides must be reduced to obtain the corresponding metals, often achieved by heating these oxides with carbon or carbon monoxide as reducing agents.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Blast furnaces are the reactors where iron oxides and coke (a form of carbon) are combined to produce molten iron.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Early theoretical research with applications to flooded soils and paddy rice production shaped subsequent work on thermodynamic aspects of redox and plant root growth in soils.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Later work extended it to redox reactions related to heavy metal oxidation state changes, pedogenesis and morphology, organic compound degradation and formation, free radical chemistry, wetland delineation, soil remediation, and methods for characterizing the redox status of soils.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] The key terms involved in redox can be confusing.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] For example, a reagent that is oxidized loses electrons; however, that reagent is referred to as the reducing agent.
[src:redox-reactions/redox] Likewise, a reagent that is reduced gains electrons and is referred to as the oxidizing agent.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] In chemistry, a **reducing agent** (also known as a **reductant**, **reducer**, or **electron donor**) is a chemical species that "donates" an electron to an *electron recipient* (called the *oxidizing agent*, *oxidant*, *oxidizer*, or *electron acceptor*).
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Examples of substances that are common reducing agents include hydrogen, carbon monoxide, the alkali metals, formic acid, oxalic acid, and sulfite compounds.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] In their pre-reaction states, reducers have extra electrons (that is, they are by themselves reduced) and oxidizers lack electrons (that is, they are by themselves oxidized).
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] This is commonly expressed in terms of their oxidation states.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] An agent's oxidation state describes its degree of loss of electrons, where the higher the oxidation state then the fewer electrons it has.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] So initially, prior to the reaction, a reducing agent is typically in one of its lower possible oxidation states; its oxidation state increases during the reaction while that of the oxidizer decreases.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The oxygen (O2) is being reduced, so it is the oxidizing agent.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The glucose (C6H12O6) is being oxidized, so it is the reducing agent.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The reducing agent in this reaction is ferrocyanide ([Fe(CN)6]4−).
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] It donates an electron, becoming oxidized to ferricyanide ([Fe(CN)6]3−).
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Simultaneously, that electron is received by the oxidizer chlorine (Cl 2), which is reduced to chloride (Cl− ).
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Strong reducing agents easily lose (or donate) electrons.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] An atom with a relatively large atomic radius tends to be a better reductant.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] In such species, the distance from the nucleus to the valence electrons is so long that these electrons are not strongly attracted.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] These elements tend to be strong reducing agents.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Good reducing agents tend to consist of atoms with a low electronegativity, which is the ability of an atom or molecule to attract bonding electrons, and species with relatively small ionization energies serve as good reducing agents too.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The measure of a material's ability to reduce is known as its reduction potential.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The table below shows a few reduction potentials, which can be changed to oxidation potentials by reversing the sign.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Reducing agents can be ranked by increasing strength by ranking their reduction potentials.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Reducers donate electrons to (that is, "reduce") oxidizing agents, which are said to "be reduced by" the reducer.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The reducing agent is stronger when it has a more negative reduction potential and weaker when it has a more positive reduction potential.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The more positive the reduction potential the greater the species' affinity for electrons and tendency to be reduced (that is, to receive electrons).
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The following table provides the reduction potentials of the indicated reducing agent at 25 °C.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] For example, among sodium (Na), chromium (Cr), cuprous (Cu+) and chloride (Cl−), it is Na that is the strongest reducing agent while Cl− is the weakest; said differently, Na+ is the weakest oxidizing agent in this list while Cl is the strongest.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Common reducing agents include metals potassium, calcium, barium, sodium and magnesium, and also compounds that contain the hydride H− ion, those being NaH, LiH, LiAlH4 and CaH2.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Some elements and compounds can be both reducing or oxidizing agents.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Hydrogen gas is a reducing agent when it reacts with non-metals and an oxidizing agent when it reacts with metals.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Hydrogen (whose reduction potential is 0.0) acts as an oxidizing agent because it accepts an electron donation from the reducing agent lithium (whose reduction potential is -3.04), which causes Li to be oxidized and hydrogen to be reduced.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Hydrogen acts as a reducing agent because it donates its electrons to fluorine, which allows fluorine to be reduced.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Reducing agents and oxidizing agents are the ones responsible for corrosion, which is the "degradation of metals as a result of electrochemical activity".
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Corrosion requires an anode and cathode to take place.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The anode is an element that loses electrons (reducing agent), thus oxidation always occurs in the anode, and the cathode is an element that gains electrons (oxidizing agent), thus reduction always occurs in the cathode.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Corrosion occurs whenever there's a difference in oxidation potential.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] When this is present, the anode metal begins deteriorating, given there is an electrical connection and the presence of an electrolyte.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Historically, reduction referred to the removal of oxygen from a compound, hence the name 'reduction'.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] By using water as a reducing agent, aquatic photosynthesizing cyanobacteria produced this molecular oxygen as a waste product.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The rate of production of oxygen eventually exceeded the availability of reducing materials that removed oxygen, which ultimately led Earth to gain a strongly oxidizing atmosphere containing abundant oxygen (like the modern atmosphere).
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] The modern sense of donating electrons is a generalization of this idea, acknowledging that other components can play a similar chemical role to oxygen.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] In the above equation, the Iron (Fe) has an oxidation number of 0 before and 3+ after the reaction.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] For oxygen (O) the oxidation number began as 0 and decreased to 2−.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Iron (Fe) has been oxidized because the oxidation number increased.
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Iron is the reducing agent because it gave electrons to the oxygen (O2).
[src:redox-reactions/reducing-agent] Oxygen (O2) has been reduced because the oxidation number has decreased and is the oxidizing agent because it took electrons from iron (Fe).
